TY  - JOUR
ID  - 33682093
VL  - 76 Suppl 4
Y1  - 2021 Apr
T1  - An update on the management of chronic pelvic pain in women.
SP  - 96-107
DO  - 10.1111/anae.15421
AB  - Chronic pelvic pain represents a major public health problem for women and  impacts significantly on their quality of life. Yet it is under-researched and a  challenge to manage. Women who suffer from chronic pelvic pain frequently  describe their healthcare journey as long, via a variety of specialists and  frustrating, with their pain often dismissed. Aetiological factors and  associations are best conceptualised using the 'three P's' model of predisposing,  precipitating and perpetuating factors. This integrates the numerous biological,  psychological and social contributors to the complex, multifactorial nature of  chronic pelvic pain. Overall management involves analgesia, hormonal therapies,  physiotherapy, psychological approaches and lifestyle advice, which like other  chronic pain conditions relies on a multidisciplinary team approach delivered by  professionals experienced and trained in managing chronic pelvic pain.
